# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ecology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:ecology/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] In ecology, **abiotic components** or **abiotic factors** are non-living chemical and physical parts of the environment that affect living organisms and the functioning of ecosystems.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors and the phenomena associated with them underpin biology as a whole.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] They affect a wide range of species, across all forms of environmental conditions, such as marine or terrestrial animals.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] Humans can make or change abiotic factors in a species' environment.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] For instance, fertilizers can affect a snail's habitat, or the greenhouse gases which humans utilize can change marine pH levels.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] Abiotic components include physical conditions and non-living resources that affect living organisms in terms of growth, maintenance, and reproduction.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] Resources are distinguished as substances or objects in the environment required by one organism and consumed or otherwise made unavailable for use by other organisms.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] Component degradation of a substance occurs by chemical or physical processes, e.g. hydrolysis.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] All non-living components of an ecosystem, such as atmospheric conditions and water resources, are called abiotic components.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] In biology, abiotic factors can include water, light, radiation, temperature, humidity, atmosphere, acidity, salinity, precipitation, altitude, minerals, tides, rain, dissolved oxygen nutrients, and soil.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] The macroscopic climate often influences each of the above.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] Pressure and sound waves may also be considered in the context of marine or sub-terrestrial environments.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors in ocean environments also include aerial exposure, substrate, water clarity, solar energy and tides.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] Consider the differences in the mechanics of C3, C4, and CAM plants in regulating the influx of carbon dioxide to the Calvin-Benson Cycle in relation to their abiotic stressors.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] C3 plants have no mechanisms to manage photorespiration, whereas C4 and CAM plants utilize a separate PEP carboxylase enzyme to prevent photorespiration, thus increasing the yield of photosynthesis processes in certain high energy environments.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] Many Archea require very high temperatures, pressures, or unusual concentrations of chemical substances such as sulfur; this is due to their specialization into extreme conditions.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] In addition, fungi have also evolved to survive at the temperature, the humidity, and stability of their environment.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] For example, there is a significant difference in access to both water and humidity between temperate rain forests and deserts.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] This difference in water availability causes a diversity in the organisms that survive in these areas.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] These differences in abiotic components alter the species present by creating boundaries of what species can survive within the environment and influencing competition between two species.
[src:ecology/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors such as salinity can give one species a competitive advantage over another, creating pressures that lead to speciation and alteration of a species to and from generalist and specialist competitors.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is essentially unavoidable.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress affects animals, but plants are especially dependent, if not solely dependent, on environmental factors, so it is particularly constraining.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is the most harmful factor concerning the growth and productivity of crops worldwide.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Research has also shown that abiotic stressors are at their most harmful when they occur together, in combinations of abiotic stress factors.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] The most common of the stressors are the easiest for people to identify, but there are many other, less recognizable abiotic stress factors which affect environments constantly.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Lesser-known stressors generally occur on a smaller scale.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] They include: poor edaphic conditions like rock content and pH levels, high radiation, compaction, contamination, and other, highly specific conditions like rapid rehydration during seed germination.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress, as a natural part of every ecosystem, will affect organisms in a variety of ways.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Although these effects may be either beneficial or detrimental, the location of the area is crucial in determining the extent of the impact that abiotic stress will have.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] The higher the latitude of the area affected, the greater the impact of abiotic stress will be on that area.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] So, a taiga or boreal forest is at the mercy of whatever abiotic stress factors may come along, while tropical zones are much less susceptible to such stressors.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] While abiotic stress may have negative impacts on individual organisms, there are cases where abiotic stress plays an important role in maintaining a healthy ecosystem.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Important ecosystem mechanisms and improved overall stress tolerance may rely on occasional low levels of abiotic stress.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] One example of a situation where abiotic stress plays a constructive role in an ecosystem is in natural wildfires.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Smaller fires are useful in reducing the overall fuel load of an area of forest or prairie.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] By clearing out dead brush and other organic matter, the risk of catastrophic and widespread fire decreases, and the residual ash of smaller fires helps add nutrients back into the soil.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] The observed benefits of these smaller and more controlled fires on land usability and species populations have led to the use of prescribed burning by humans for centuries.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Varying perspectives on the benefits and risks of fire to ecosystems have influenced official policy through history.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Forest Service, initially focused on fire control, changed its policy to one of fire management in 1974, recognizing these fires as a natural part of an ecosystem.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] There is also evidence that a diverse fire history between patches of land within an area has been shown to benefit transitional landscapes between savanna and forest.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Even though it is healthy for an ecosystem, a wildfire can still be considered an abiotic stressor, because it puts stress on individual organisms within the area.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] On the larger scale, though, natural wildfires are positive manifestations of abiotic stress.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] What also needs to be taken into account when looking for benefits of abiotic stress, is that one phenomenon may not affect an entire ecosystem in the same way.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] While a flood will kill most plants living low on the ground in a certain area, if there is rice there, it will thrive in the wet conditions.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Another example of this is in phytoplankton and zooplankton.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] The same types of conditions are usually considered stressful for these two types of organisms.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] They act very similarly when exposed to ultraviolet light and most toxins, but at elevated temperatures the phytoplankton reacts negatively, while the thermophilic zooplankton reacts positively to the increase in temperature.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] The two may be living in the same environment, but an increase in temperature of the area would prove stressful only for one of the organisms.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Lastly, abiotic stress has enabled species to grow, develop, and evolve, through the process of natural selection.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Heritable traits that improve an organism's resiliency under stressed conditions increase the likelihood that the organism will survive and reproduce, enabling it to pass these traits to the next generation.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Both plants and animals have evolved mechanisms allowing them to survive extremes.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] One of the detriments concerning abiotic stress involves farming.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] It has been claimed by one study that abiotic stress causes the most crop loss of any other factor and that most major crops are reduced in their yield by more than 50% from their potential yield.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Because abiotic stress is widely considered a detrimental effect, the research on this branch of the issue is extensive.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] For more information on the harmful effects of abiotic stress, see the sections below on plants and animals.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] A plant's first line of defense against abiotic stress is in its roots.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] If the soil holding the plant is healthy and biologically diverse, the plant will have a higher chance of surviving stressful conditions.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] The plant responses to stress are dependent on the tissue or organ affected by the stress.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] For example, transcriptional responses to stress are tissue or cell specific in roots and are quite different depending on the stress involved.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] One of the primary responses to abiotic stress such as high salinity is the disruption of the Na+/K+ ratio in the cytoplasm of the plant cell.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] High concentrations of Na+, for example, can decrease the capacity for the plant to take up water and also alter enzyme and transporter functions.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Evolved adaptations to efficiently restore cellular ion homeostasis have led to a wide variety of stress tolerant plants.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Facilitation, or the positive interactions between different species of plants, is an intricate web of association in a natural environment.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] In areas of high stress, the level of facilitation is especially high as well.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] This could possibly be because the plants need a stronger network to survive in a harsher environment, so their interactions between species, such as cross-pollination or mutualistic actions, become more common to cope with the severity of their habitat.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Plants also adapt very differently from one another, even from a plant living in the same area.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] When a group of different plant species was prompted by a variety of different stress signals, such as drought or cold, each plant responded uniquely.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Hardly any of the responses were similar, even though the plants had become accustomed to exactly the same home environment.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Serpentine soils (media with low concentrations of nutrients and high concentrations of heavy metals) can be a source of abiotic stress.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Initially, the absorption of toxic metal ions is limited by cell membrane exclusion.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Ions that are absorbed into tissues are sequestered in cell vacuoles.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] This sequestration mechanism is facilitated by proteins on the vacuole membrane.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] An example of plants that adapt to serpentine soil are Metallophytes, or hyperaccumulators, as they are known for their ability to absorbed heavy metals using the root-to-shoot translocation (which it will absorb into shoots rather than the plant itself).
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] They're also extinguished for their ability to absorb toxic substances from heavy metals.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Chemical priming has been proposed to increase tolerance to abiotic stresses in crop plants.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] In this method, which is analogous to vaccination, stress-inducing chemical agents are introduced to the plant in brief doses so that the plant begins preparing defense mechanisms.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Thus, when the abiotic stress occurs, the plant has already prepared defense mechanisms that can be activated faster and increase tolerance.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress mostly affects plants used in agriculture.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Some examples of adverse conditions (which may be caused by climate change) are high or low temperatures, drought, salinity, and toxins.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Elevated global temperatures present a severe bottleneck for crop yields, as heat stress alters membrane fluidity, accelerates destructive transpiration rates, and heavily impairs a plant's overall Water Use Efficiency (WUE).
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] When crops encounter extreme thermal environments during early reproductive or vegetative stages, cellular homeostasis is broken down, causing grain yield reduction and premature leaf senescence.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] To mitigate down-stream damage from overlapping thermal and drought shocks, advanced ex-ante strategies such as physical seed priming or chemical priming agents are applied.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] These priming interventions activate early molecular, enzymatic, and hormonal pre-defense responses within the seed tissue, enabling the plant to maintain higher functional stability and lower oxidative injury when heat stress occurs later in the field environment.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Flooding acts as a compound environmental stressor that is broadly categorized into waterlogging (where only the root system is inundated) and complete submergence (where the entire plant is covered by water).
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] The primary hazard of flooding is gas diffusion restriction, which triggers oxygen starvation (hypoxia or anoxia) in the rhizosphere and alters essential plant hormone signaling networks, such as the regulation between Sub1A and non-Sub1A genotypes in rice.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] To cope with complete submergence, tolerant plants rely on distinct physiological survival strategies.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Furthermore, monitoring maximum quantum yield performance reveals that preserving photosynthetic efficiency during transient flooding stress is paramount to driving rapid physiological recovery once the water recedes.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Soil acidity acts as a sweeping abiotic stress factor on global arable lands, primarily because low pH environments trigger dangerous chemical toxicities dominated by soluble aluminum (Al3+ )and iron, which structurally damage root anatomy and limit basic development.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] High acidity also locks up vital macronutrients, causing severe phosphorus starvation stress that forces plants to aggressively modify their lateral root structures to maximize surface area absorption.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] To remediate heavy-metal-polluted and highly acidic substrates, bioremediation utilizes hyperaccumulator plant traits (metallophytes).
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] These specialized plants successfully survive the toxicity of acidic media by relying on a highly developed root-to-shoot translocation system, which efficiently absorbs and transports toxic ions away from fragile root tissues and sequesters them safely inside the upper shoot vacuoles.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Soil salinization, the accumulation of water-soluble salts to levels that negatively impact plant production, is a global phenomenon affecting approximately 831 million hectares of land.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] More specifically, the phenomenon threatens 19.5% of the world's irrigated agricultural land and 2.1% of the world's non-irrigated (dry-land) agricultural lands.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] High soil salinity content can be harmful to plants because water-soluble salts can alter osmotic potential gradients and consequently inhibit many cellular functions.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Over generations, many plants have mutated and built different mechanisms to counter salinity effects.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] A good combatant of salinity in plants is the hormone ethylene.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Ethylene is known for regulating plant growth and development and dealing with stress conditions.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Many central membrane proteins in plants, such as ETO2, ERS1 and EIN2, are used for ethylene signaling in many plant growth processes.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Mutations in these proteins can lead to heightened salt sensitivity and can limit plant growth.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] The effects of salinity has been studied on *Arabidopsis* plants that have mutated ERS1, ERS2, ETR1, ETR2 and EIN4 proteins.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] These proteins are used for ethylene signaling against certain stress conditions, such as salt and the ethylene precursor ACC is used to suppress any sensitivity to the salt stress.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus (P) is an essential macronutrient required for plant growth and development, but it is present only in limited quantities in most of the world's soil.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Plants use P mainly in the form of soluble inorganic phosphates (PO4−−−) but are subject to abiotic stress when there is not enough soluble PO4−−− in the soil.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus forms insoluble complexes with Ca and Mg in alkaline soils and with Al and Fe in acidic soils that make the phosphorus unavailable for plant roots.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] It has been shown that PHR1, a MYB-related transcription factor, is a master regulator of P-starvation response in plants.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Drought stress, defined as naturally occurring water deficit, is a main cause of crop losses in agriculture.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] This is because water is essential for many fundamental processes in plant growth.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] It has become especially important in recent years to find a way to combat drought stress.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] A decrease in precipitation and consequent increase in drought are extremely likely in the future due to an increase in global warming.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Plants have come up with many mechanisms and adaptations to try and deal with drought stress.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] One of the leading ways that plants combat drought stress is by closing their stomata.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] A key hormone regulating stomatal opening and closing is abscisic acid (ABA).
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Synthesis of ABA causes the ABA to bind to receptors.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] This binding then affects the opening of ion channels, thereby decreasing turgor pressure in the stomata and causing them to close.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Recent studies by Gonzalez-Villagra, et al., have shown how ABA levels increased in drought-stressed plants (2018).
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] They showed that when plants were placed in a stressful situation, they produced more ABA to try to conserve any water they had in their leaves.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Another extremely important factor in dealing with drought stress and regulating the uptake and export of water is aquaporins (AQPs).
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] AQPs are integral membrane proteins that make up channels.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] These channels' main job is the transport of water and other essential solutes.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] AQPs are both transcriptionally and post-transcriptionally regulated by many different factors such as ABA, GA3, pH and Ca2+; and the specific levels of AQPs in certain parts of the plant, such as roots or leaves, helps to draw as much water into the plant as possible.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] By understanding the mechanisms of both AQPs and the hormone ABA, scientists will be better able to produce drought-resistant plants in the future.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] A study by Tombesi et al., found that plants which had previously been exposed to drought were able to minimize water loss and decrease water use.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] They found that plants which were exposed to drought conditions actually changed the way they regulated their stomata and what they called "hydraulic safety margin" so as to decrease the vulnerability of the plant.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] By changing the regulation of stomata and subsequently the transpiration, plants were able to function better when less water was available.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] For animals, the most stressful of all the abiotic stressors is heat.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] This is because many species are unable to regulate their internal body temperature.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Even in the species that are able to regulate their own temperature, it is not always a completely accurate system.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Temperature determines metabolic rates, heart rates, and other very important factors within the bodies of animals, so an extreme temperature change can easily distress the animal's body.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Animals can respond to extreme heat, for example, through natural heat acclimation or by burrowing into the ground to find a cooler space.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] It is also possible to see in animals that a high genetic diversity is beneficial in providing resiliency against harsh abiotic stressors.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] This acts as a sort of stock room when a species is plagued by the perils of natural selection.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] A variety of galling insects are among the most specialized and diverse herbivores on the planet, and their extensive protections against abiotic stress factors have helped the insect in gaining that position of honor.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Biodiversity is determined by many things, and one of them is abiotic stress.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] If an environment is highly stressful, biodiversity tends to be low.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] If abiotic stress does not have a strong presence in an area, the biodiversity will be much higher.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] This idea leads into the understanding of how abiotic stress and endangered species are related.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] It has been observed through a variety of environments that as the level of abiotic stress increases, the number of species decreases.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] This means that species are more likely to become population threatened, endangered, and even extinct, when and where abiotic stress is especially harsh.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Data suggests that anthropogenic activity has increased the global temperature, and likely increased the odds of extreme climate events such as drought, fire conditions and flooding.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] Threats to organisms and ecosystem biodiversity due to increased abiotic stress are one major impact of this change.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] The effects of climate change on biomes vary due to the location, patterns of precipitation, and the organisms which inhabit them.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] On the species level, the increased abiotic stress due to climate change can lead to adaptations which increase a species' reproductive success under these conditions.
[src:ecology/abiotic-stress] However, such highly specialized adaptations may leave species vulnerable to other stresses.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] In ecology, **local abundance** is the relative representation of a species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] It is usually measured as the number of individuals found per sample.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] The ratio of abundance of one species to one or multiple other species living in an ecosystem is referred to as relative species abundances.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] Both indicators are relevant for computing biodiversity.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] A variety of sampling methods are used to measure abundance.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] For larger animals, these may include spotlight counts, track counts and roadkill counts, as well as presence at monitoring stations.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] In many plant communities the abundances of plant species are measured by plant cover, i.e. the relative area covered by different plant species in a small plot.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] Abundance is in simplest terms usually measured by identifying and counting every individual of every species in a given sector.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] It is common for the distribution of species to be skewed so that a few species take up the bulk of individuals collected.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] Relative species abundance is calculated by dividing the number of species from one group by the total number of species from all groups.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] These measures are all a part of community ecology.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] Understanding patterns within a community is easy when the community has a relatively low number of species.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] However most communities do not have a low number of species.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] Measuring species abundance allows for understanding of how species are distributed within an ecosystem.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] For example, salt water marshes have an influx of sea water, causing only a few species which are adapted to be able to survive in both salt and fresh water to be abundant.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] Inversely in land locked wetlands, the species abundance is more evenly distributed among the species who live within the wetland.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] In most ecosystems in which abundance has been calculated, most often only a small number of species are abundant, while a large number are pretty rare.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] These abundant species are often generalists, with many rare species being specialists.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] High density of a species in multiple localities will usually lead to it being relatively abundant over all in an ecosystem.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] Therefore, high local abundance can be directly linked to high regional distribution.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] Species with high abundance are likely to have more offspring, and these offspring in turn are more likely to colonize a new sector of the ecosystem than a species which is less abundant.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] Thus begins a positive feedback loop leading to a species distribution in which a few "core species" are wide spread, and the other species are restricted and scarce known as satellite species.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] Species abundance distribution (SAD) is one of the main uses of this measurement.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] SAD is a measurement of how common, or rare species are within an ecosystem.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] This allows researchers to assess how different species are distributed throughout an ecosystem.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] SAD is one of the most basic measurements in ecology and is used very often, therefore many different methods of measurement and analysis have developed.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] There are several methods for measuring abundance.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] An example of this is Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] These are measurement methods which involve estimation based on viewing a specific area of a designated size.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] The two Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings used are known as the D.A.F.O.R, and the A.C.F.O.R.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] These methods are useful for getting a rough estimate of the species abundance in a designated area (quadrant), but they are not exact or objective measurements.
[src:ecology/abundance-ecology] Therefore, if another method of measuring abundance is available, it should be used, as this will lead to more useful and quantifiable data.
[src:ecology/adaptation] In biology, **adaptation** has three related meanings.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Firstly, it is the dynamic evolutionary process of natural selection that fits organisms to their environment, enhancing their evolutionary fitness.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Secondly, it is a state reached by the population during that process.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Thirdly, it is a phenotypic trait or **adaptive trait**, with a functional role in each individual organism, that is maintained and has evolved through natural selection.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Historically, adaptation has been described from the time of the ancient Greek philosophers such as Empedocles and Aristotle.
[src:ecology/adaptation] In 18th and 19th-century natural theology, adaptation was taken as evidence for the existence of a deity.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Charles Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace proposed instead that it was explained by natural selection.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Adaptation is related to biological fitness, which governs the rate of evolution as measured by changes in allele frequencies.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Often, two or more species co-adapt and co-evolve as they develop adaptations that interlock with those of the other species, such as with flowering plants and pollinating insects.
[src:ecology/adaptation] In mimicry, species evolve to resemble other species; in mimicry this is a mutually beneficial co-evolution as each of a group of strongly defended species (such as wasps able to sting) come to advertise their defences in the same way.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Features evolved for one purpose may be co-opted for a different one, as when the insulating feathers of dinosaurs were co-opted for bird flight.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Adaptation is a major topic in the philosophy of biology, as it concerns function and purpose (teleology).
[src:ecology/adaptation] Some biologists try to avoid terms which imply purpose in adaptation, not least because they suggest a deity's intentions, but others note that adaptation is necessarily purposeful.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Adaptation is an observable fact of life accepted by philosophers and natural historians from ancient times, independently of their views on evolution, but their explanations differed.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Empedocles did not believe that adaptation required a final cause (a purpose), but thought that it "came about naturally, since such things survived." Aristotle did believe in final causes, but assumed that species were fixed.
[src:ecology/adaptation] In natural theology, adaptation was interpreted as the work of a deity and as evidence for the existence of God.
[src:ecology/adaptation] William Paley believed that organisms were perfectly adapted to the lives they led, an argument that shadowed Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, who had argued that God had brought about "the best of all possible worlds." Voltaire's satire Dr.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Pangloss is a parody of this optimistic idea, and David Hume also argued against design.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Charles Darwin broke with the tradition by emphasising the flaws and limitations which occurred in the animal and plant worlds.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Jean-Baptiste Lamarck proposed a tendency for organisms to become more complex, moving up a ladder of progress, plus "the influence of circumstances", usually expressed as *use and disuse*.
[src:ecology/adaptation] This second, subsidiary element of his theory is what is now called Lamarckism, a proto-evolutionary hypothesis of the inheritance of acquired characteristics, intended to explain adaptations by natural means.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Other natural historians, such as Buffon, accepted adaptation, and some also accepted evolution, without voicing their opinions as to the mechanism.
[src:ecology/adaptation] This illustrates the real merit of Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace, and secondary figures such as Henry Walter Bates, for putting forward a mechanism whose significance had only been glimpsed previously.
[src:ecology/adaptation] A century later, experimental field studies and breeding experiments by people such as E.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Ford and Theodosius Dobzhansky produced evidence that natural selection was not only the 'engine' behind adaptation, but was a much stronger force than had previously been thought.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Adaptation is primarily a process rather than a physical form or part of a body.
[src:ecology/adaptation] An internal parasite (such as a liver fluke) can illustrate the distinction: such a parasite may have a very simple bodily structure, but nevertheless the organism is highly adapted to its specific environment.
[src:ecology/adaptation] From this we see that adaptation is not just a matter of visible traits: in such parasites critical adaptations take place in the life cycle, which is often quite complex.
[src:ecology/adaptation] However, as a practical term, "adaptation" often refers to a *product*: those features of a species which result from the process.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Many aspects of an animal or plant can be correctly called adaptations, though there are always some features whose function remains in doubt.
[src:ecology/adaptation] By using the term *adaptation* for the evolutionary *process*, and *adaptive trait* for the bodily part or function (the product), one may distinguish the two different senses of the word.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Adaptation is one of the two main processes that explain the observed diversity of species, such as the different species of Darwin's finches.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The other process is speciation, in which new species arise, typically through reproductive isolation.
[src:ecology/adaptation] An example widely used today to study the interplay of adaptation and speciation is the evolution of cichlid fish in African lakes, where the question of reproductive isolation is complex.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Adaptation is not always a simple matter where the ideal phenotype evolves for a given environment.
[src:ecology/adaptation] An organism must be viable at all stages of its development and at all stages of its evolution.
[src:ecology/adaptation] This places *constraints* on the evolution of development, behaviour, and structure of organisms.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The main constraint, over which there has been much debate, is the requirement that each genetic and phenotypic change during evolution should be relatively small, because developmental systems are so complex and interlinked.
[src:ecology/adaptation] However, it is not clear what "relatively small" should mean, for example polyploidy in plants is a reasonably common large genetic change.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The origin of eukaryotic endosymbiosis is a more dramatic example.
[src:ecology/adaptation] All adaptations help organisms survive in their ecological niches.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The adaptive traits may be structural, behavioural or physiological.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Structural adaptations are physical features of an organism, such as shape, body covering, armament, and internal organization.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Behavioural adaptations are inherited systems of behaviour, whether inherited in detail as instincts, or as a neuropsychological capacity for learning.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Examples include searching for food, mating, and vocalizations.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Physiological adaptations permit the organism to perform special functions such as making venom, secreting slime, and phototropism, but also involve more general functions such as growth and development, temperature regulation, ionic balance and other aspects of homeostasis.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Adaptation affects all aspects of the life of an organism.
[src:ecology/adaptation] is the state of being adapted: the degree to which an organism is able to live and reproduce in a given set of habitats.
[src:ecology/adaptation] is an aspect of the developmental pattern of the organism which enables or enhances the probability of that organism surviving and reproducing.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Adaptation differs from flexibility, acclimatization, and learning, all of which are changes during life which are not inherited.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Flexibility deals with the relative capacity of an organism to maintain itself in different habitats: its degree of specialization.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Acclimatization describes automatic physiological adjustments during life; learning means alteration in behavioural performance during life.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Flexibility stems from phenotypic plasticity, the ability of an organism with a given genotype (genetic type) to change its phenotype (observable characteristics) in response to changes in its habitat, or to move to a different habitat.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The degree of flexibility is inherited, and varies between individuals.
[src:ecology/adaptation] A highly specialized animal or plant lives only in a well-defined habitat, eats a specific type of food, and cannot survive if its needs are not met.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Many herbivores are like this; extreme examples are koalas which depend on *Eucalyptus*, and giant pandas which require bamboo.
[src:ecology/adaptation] A generalist, on the other hand, eats a range of food, and can survive in many different conditions.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Examples are humans, rats, crabs and many carnivores.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The *tendency* to behave in a specialized or exploratory manner is inherited—it is an adaptation.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Rather different is developmental flexibility: "An animal or plant is developmentally flexible if when it is raised in or transferred to new conditions, it changes in structure so that it is better fitted to survive in the new environment," writes the evolutionary biologist John Maynard Smith.
[src:ecology/adaptation] If humans move to a higher altitude, respiration and physical exertion become a problem, but after spending time in high altitude conditions they acclimatize to the reduced partial pressure of oxygen, such as by producing more red blood cells.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The ability to acclimatize is an adaptation, but the acclimatization itself is not.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The reproductive rate declines, but deaths from some tropical diseases also go down.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Over a longer period of time, some people are better able to reproduce at high altitudes than others.
[src:ecology/adaptation] They contribute more heavily to later generations, and gradually by natural selection the whole population becomes adapted to the new conditions.
[src:ecology/adaptation] This has demonstrably occurred, as the observed performance of long-term communities at higher altitude is significantly better than the performance of new arrivals, even when the new arrivals have had time to acclimatize.
[src:ecology/adaptation] There is a relationship between adaptedness and the concept of fitness used in population genetics.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Differences in fitness between genotypes predict the rate of evolution by natural selection.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Natural selection changes the relative frequencies of alternative phenotypes, insofar as they are heritable.
[src:ecology/adaptation] However, a phenotype with high adaptedness may not have high fitness.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Dobzhansky mentioned the example of the Californian redwood, which is highly adapted, but a relict species in danger of extinction.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Elliott Sober commented that adaptation was a retrospective concept since it implied something about the history of a trait, whereas fitness predicts a trait's future.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The absolute contribution to the next generation by a genotype or a class of genotypes.
[src:ecology/adaptation] when applied to the population as a whole.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The extent to which a phenotype fits its local ecological niche.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Sewall Wright proposed that populations occupy *adaptive peaks* on a fitness landscape.
[src:ecology/adaptation] To evolve to another, higher peak, a population would first have to pass through a valley of maladaptive intermediate stages, and might be "trapped" on a peak that is not optimally adapted.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Before Darwin, adaptation was seen as a fixed relationship between an organism and its habitat.
[src:ecology/adaptation] It was not appreciated that as the climate changed, so did the habitat; and as the habitat changed, so did the biota.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Also, habitats are subject to changes in their biota: for example, invasions of species from other areas.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The relative numbers of species in a given habitat are always changing.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Change is the rule, though much depends on the speed and degree of the change.
[src:ecology/adaptation] When the habitat changes, three main things may happen to a resident population: habitat tracking, genetic change or extinction.
[src:ecology/adaptation] In fact, all three things may occur in sequence.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Of these three effects only genetic change brings about adaptation.
[src:ecology/adaptation] When a habitat changes, the resident population typically moves to more suitable places; this is the typical response of flying insects or oceanic organisms, which have wide (though not unlimited) opportunity for movement.
[src:ecology/adaptation] This common response is called *habitat tracking*.
[src:ecology/adaptation] It is one explanation put forward for the periods of apparent stasis in the fossil record (the punctuated equilibrium theory).
[src:ecology/adaptation] Without mutation, the ultimate source of all genetic variation, there would be no genetic changes and no subsequent adaptation through evolution by natural selection.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Genetic change occurs in a population when mutation increases or decreases in its initial frequency followed by random genetic drift, migration, recombination or natural selection act on this genetic variation.
[src:ecology/adaptation] One example is that the first pathways of enzyme-based metabolism at the very origin of life on Earth may have been co-opted components of the already-existing purine nucleotide metabolism, a metabolic pathway that evolved in an ancient RNA world.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The co-option requires new mutations and through natural selection, the population then adapts genetically to its present circumstances.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Genetic changes may result in entirely new or gradual change to visible structures, or they may adjust physiological activity in a way that suits the habitat.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The varying shapes of the beaks of Darwin's finches, for example, are driven by adaptive mutations in the ALX1 gene.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The coat color of different wild mouse species matches their environments, whether black lava or light sand, owing to adaptive mutations in the melanocortin 1 receptor and other melanin pathway genes.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Physiological resistance to the heart poisons (cardiac glycosides) that monarch butterflies store in their bodies to protect themselves from predators are driven by adaptive mutations in the target of the poison, the sodium pump, resulting in target site insensitivity.
[src:ecology/adaptation] These same adaptive mutations and similar changes at the same amino acid sites were found to evolve in a parallel manner in distantly related insects that feed on the same plants, and even in a bird that feeds on monarchs through convergent evolution, a hallmark of adaptation.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Convergence at the gene-level across distantly related species can arise because of evolutionary constraint.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Habitats and biota do frequently change over time and space.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Therefore, it follows that the process of adaptation is never fully complete.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Over time, it may happen that the environment changes little, and the species comes to fit its surroundings better and better, resulting in stabilizing selection.
[src:ecology/adaptation] On the other hand, it may happen that changes in the environment occur suddenly, and then the species becomes less and less well adapted.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The only way for it to climb back up that fitness peak is via the introduction of new genetic variation for natural selection to act upon.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Seen like this, adaptation is a genetic *tracking process*, which goes on all the time to some extent, but especially when the population cannot or does not move to another, less hostile area.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Given enough genetic change, as well as specific demographic conditions, an adaptation may be enough to bring a population back from the brink of extinction in a process called evolutionary rescue.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Adaptation does affect, to some extent, every species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Leigh Van Valen thought that even in a stable environment, because of antagonistic species interactions and limited resources, a species must constantly had to adapt to maintain its relative standing.
[src:ecology/adaptation] This became known as the Red Queen hypothesis, as seen in host-parasite interactions.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Existing genetic variation and mutation were the traditional sources of material on which natural selection could act.
[src:ecology/adaptation] In addition, horizontal gene transfer is possible between organisms in different species, using mechanisms as varied as gene cassettes, plasmids, transposons and viruses such as bacteriophages.
[src:ecology/adaptation] In coevolution, where the existence of one species is tightly bound up with the life of another species, new or 'improved' adaptations which occur in one species are often followed by the appearance and spread of corresponding features in the other species.
[src:ecology/adaptation] In other words, each species triggers reciprocal natural selection in the other.
[src:ecology/adaptation] These co-adaptational relationships are intrinsically dynamic, and may continue on a trajectory for millions of years, as has occurred in the relationship between flowering plants and pollinating insects.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Bates' work on Amazonian butterflies led him to develop the first scientific account of mimicry, especially the kind of mimicry which bears his name: Batesian mimicry.
[src:ecology/adaptation] This is the mimicry by a palatable species of an unpalatable or noxious species (the model), gaining a selective advantage as predators avoid the model and therefore also the mimic.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Mimicry is thus an anti-predator adaptation.
[src:ecology/adaptation] A common example seen in temperate gardens is the hoverfly (Syrphidae), many of which—though bearing no sting—mimic the warning coloration of aculeate Hymenoptera (wasps and bees).
[src:ecology/adaptation] Such mimicry does not need to be perfect to improve the survival of the palatable species.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Bates, Wallace and Fritz Müller believed that Batesian and Müllerian mimicry provided evidence for the action of natural selection, a view which is now standard amongst biologists.
[src:ecology/adaptation] All adaptations have a downside: horse legs are great for running on grass, but they cannot scratch their backs; mammals' hair helps temperature, but offers a niche for ectoparasites; the only flying penguins do is under water.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Adaptations serving different functions may be mutually destructive.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Compromise and makeshift occur widely, not perfection.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Selection pressures pull in different directions, and the adaptation that results is some kind of compromise.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Consider the antlers of the Irish elk, (often supposed to be far too large; in deer antler size has an allometric relationship to body size).
[src:ecology/adaptation] Antlers serve positively for defence against predators, and to score victories in the annual rut.
[src:ecology/adaptation] But they are costly in terms of resources.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Their size during the last glacial period presumably depended on the relative gain and loss of reproductive capacity in the population of elks during that time.
[src:ecology/adaptation] As another example, camouflage to avoid detection is destroyed when vivid coloration is displayed at mating time.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Here the risk to life is counterbalanced by the necessity for reproduction.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Stream-dwelling salamanders, such as Caucasian salamander or Gold-striped salamander have very slender, long bodies, perfectly adapted to life at the banks of fast small rivers and mountain brooks.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Elongated body protects their larvae from being washed out by current.
[src:ecology/adaptation] However, elongated body increases risk of desiccation and decreases dispersal ability of the salamanders; it also negatively affects their fecundity.
[src:ecology/adaptation] As a result, fire salamander, less perfectly adapted to the mountain brook habitats, is in general more successful, have a higher fecundity and broader geographic range.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The peacock's ornamental train (grown anew in time for each mating season) is a famous adaptation.
[src:ecology/adaptation] It must reduce his maneuverability and flight, and is hugely conspicuous; also, its growth costs food resources.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The recognition of sexual selection was for a long time in abeyance, but has been rehabilitated.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The conflict between the size of the human foetal brain at birth, (which cannot be larger than about 400 cm3, else it will not get through the mother's pelvis) and the size needed for an adult brain (about 1400 cm3), means the brain of a newborn child is quite immature.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The most vital things in human life (locomotion, speech) just have to wait while the brain grows and matures.
[src:ecology/adaptation] That is the result of the birth compromise.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Much of the problem comes from our upright bipedal stance, without which our pelvis could be shaped more suitably for birth.
[src:ecology/adaptation] As another example, the long neck of a giraffe brings benefits but at a cost.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The neck of a giraffe can be up to 2 m (6 ft 7 in) in length.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The benefits are that it can be used for inter-species competition or for foraging on tall trees where shorter herbivores cannot reach.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The cost is that a long neck is heavy and adds to the animal's body mass, requiring additional energy to build the neck and to carry its weight around.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Pre-adaptation occurs when a population has characteristics which by chance are suited for a set of conditions not previously experienced.
[src:ecology/adaptation] For example, the polyploid cordgrass *Spartina townsendii* is better adapted than either of its parent species to their own habitat of saline marsh and mud-flats.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Among domestic animals, the White Leghorn chicken is markedly more resistant to vitamin B1 deficiency than other breeds; on a plentiful diet this makes no difference, but on a restricted diet this preadaptation could be decisive.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Pre-adaptation may arise because a natural population carries a huge quantity of genetic variability.
[src:ecology/adaptation] In diploid eukaryotes, this is a consequence of the system of sexual reproduction, where mutant alleles get partially shielded, for example, by genetic dominance.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Microorganisms, with their huge populations, also carry a great deal of genetic variability.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The word is controversial because it is teleological and the entire concept of natural selection depends on the presence of genetic variation, regardless of the population size of a species in question.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Features that now appear as adaptations sometimes arose by co-option of existing traits, evolved for some other purpose.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The classic example is the ear ossicles of mammals, which we know from paleontological and embryological evidence originated in the upper and lower jaws and the hyoid bone of their synapsid ancestors, and further back still were part of the gill arches of early fish.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The word *exaptation* was coined to cover these common evolutionary shifts in function.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The flight feathers of birds evolved from the much earlier feathers of dinosaurs, which might have been used for insulation or for display.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Animals including earthworms, beavers and humans use some of their adaptations to modify their surroundings, so as to maximize their chances of surviving and reproducing.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Beavers create dams and lodges, changing the ecosystems of the valleys around them.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Earthworms, as Darwin noted, improve the topsoil in which they live by incorporating organic matter.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Humans have constructed extensive civilizations with cities in environments as varied as the Arctic and hot deserts.
[src:ecology/adaptation] In all three cases, the construction and maintenance of ecological niches helps drive the continued selection of the genes of these animals, in an environment that the animals have modified.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Some traits do not appear to be adaptive as they have a neutral or deleterious effect on fitness in the current environment.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Another possibility is that a trait may have been adaptive at some point in an organism's evolutionary history, but a change in habitats caused what used to be an adaptation to become unnecessary or even maladapted.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Many organisms have vestigial organs, which are the remnants of fully functional structures in their ancestors.
[src:ecology/adaptation] As a result of changes in lifestyle the organs became redundant, and are either not functional or reduced in functionality.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Since any structure represents some kind of cost to the general economy of the body, an advantage may accrue from their elimination once they are not functional.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Examples: wisdom teeth in humans; the loss of pigment and functional eyes in cave fauna; the loss of structure in endoparasites.
[src:ecology/adaptation] If a population cannot move or change sufficiently to preserve its long-term viability, then it will become extinct, at least in that locale.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The species may or may not survive in other locales.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Species extinction occurs when the death rate over the entire species exceeds the birth rate for a long enough period for the species to disappear.
[src:ecology/adaptation] It was an observation of Van Valen that groups of species tend to have a characteristic and fairly regular rate of extinction.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The first stage in the evolution of life on earth is often hypothesized to be the RNA world in which short self-replicating RNA molecules proliferated before the evolution of DNA and proteins.
[src:ecology/adaptation] By this hypothesis, life started when RNA chains began to self-replicate, initiating the three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation of type, and competition for resources.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The fitness of an RNA replicator (its per capita rate of increase) would likely have been a function of its intrinsic adaptive capacities, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and the availability of resources.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The three primary adaptive capacities may have been: (1) replication with moderate fidelity, giving rise to heritability while allowing variation of type, (2) resistance to decay, and (3) acquisition of resources.
[src:ecology/adaptation] These adaptive capacities would have been determined by the folded configurations of the RNA replicators resulting from their nucleotide sequences.
[src:ecology/adaptation] In his biology, Aristotle introduced teleology to describe the adaptedness of organisms, but without accepting the supernatural intention built into Plato's thinking, which Aristotle rejected.
[src:ecology/adaptation] Modern biologists continue to face the same difficulty.
[src:ecology/adaptation] On the one hand, adaptation is purposeful: natural selection chooses what works and eliminates what does not.
[src:ecology/adaptation] On the other hand, biologists by and large reject conscious purpose in evolution.
[src:ecology/adaptation] The dilemma gave rise to a famous joke by the evolutionary biologist Haldane: "Teleology is like a mistress to a biologist: he cannot live without her but he's unwilling to be seen with her in public.'" David Hull commented that Haldane's mistress "has become a lawfully wedded wife.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecology addresses the full scale of life, from tiny bacteria to processes that span the entire planet.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecology is a branch of biology, and is the study of abundance, biomass, and distribution of organisms in the context of the environment.
[src:ecology/ecology] It encompasses life processes, interactions, and adaptations; movement of materials and energy through living communities; successional development of ecosystems; cooperation, competition, and predation within and between species; and patterns of biodiversity and its effect on ecosystem processes.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecology has practical applications in fields such as conservation biology, wetland management, natural resource management, and human ecology.
[src:ecology/ecology] The term *ecology* (German: *Ökologie*) was coined in 1866 by the German scientist Ernst Haeckel.
[src:ecology/ecology] The science of ecology as it is known today began with a group of American botanists in the 1890s.
[src:ecology/ecology] Evolutionary concepts relating to adaptation and natural selection are cornerstones of modern ecological theory.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecosystems are dynamically interacting systems of organisms, the communities they make up, and the non-living (abiotic) components of their environment.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecosystem processes, such as primary production, nutrient cycling, and niche construction, regulate the flux of energy and matter through an environment.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecosystems have biophysical feedback mechanisms that moderate processes acting on living (biotic) and abiotic components of the planet.
[src:ecology/ecology] A single tree is of little consequence to the classification of a forest ecosystem, but is critically relevant to organisms living in and on it.
[src:ecology/ecology] Several generations of an aphid population can exist over the lifespan of a single leaf.
[src:ecology/ecology] Each of those aphids, in turn, supports diverse bacterial communities.
[src:ecology/ecology] The nature of connections in ecological communities cannot be explained by knowing the details of each species in isolation, because the emergent pattern is neither revealed nor predicted until the ecosystem is studied as an integrated whole.
[src:ecology/ecology] The main subdisciplines of ecology, population (or community) ecology and ecosystem ecology, differ in their contrasting paradigms.
[src:ecology/ecology] The former focuses on organisms' distribution and abundance, while the latter focuses on materials and energy fluxes.
[src:ecology/ecology] To structure the study of ecology into a conceptually manageable framework, the biological world is organized into a hierarchy, ranging in scale from (as far as ecology is concerned) organisms, to populations, to guilds, to communities, to ecosystems, to biomes, and up to the level of the biosphere.
[src:ecology/ecology] Biodiversity (an abbreviation of "biological diversity") describes the diversity of life from genes to ecosystems and spans every level of biological organization.
[src:ecology/ecology] The term has several interpretations, and there are many ways to index, measure, characterize, and represent its complex organization.
[src:ecology/ecology] Biodiversity includes species diversity, ecosystem diversity, and genetic diversity and scientists are interested in the way that this diversity affects the complex ecological processes operating at and among these respective levels.
[src:ecology/ecology] Biodiversity plays an important role in ecosystem services which by definition maintain and improve human quality of life.
[src:ecology/ecology] It delivers ecosystem services across heterogeneous real-world landscapes, influenced by human management and environmental conditions.
[src:ecology/ecology] Conservation priorities and management techniques require different approaches and considerations to address the full ecological scope of biodiversity.
[src:ecology/ecology] Natural capital that supports populations is critical for maintaining ecosystem services and species migration (e.g., riverine fish runs and avian insect control) has been implicated as one mechanism by which those service losses are experienced.
[src:ecology/ecology] An understanding of biodiversity has practical applications for species and ecosystem-level conservation planners as they make management recommendations to consulting firms, governments, and industry.
[src:ecology/ecology] The habitat of a species describes the environment over which it occurs and the type of community that is formed.
[src:ecology/ecology] Evelyn Hutchinson introduced "the set of biotic and abiotic conditions in which a species is able to persist and maintain stable population sizes." The niche is a central concept in the ecology of organisms and is sub-divided into *fundamental* and *realized* niches.
[src:ecology/ecology] The fundamental niche is the set of environmental conditions under which a species is able to persist.
[src:ecology/ecology] The realized niche is the set of environmental plus ecological conditions under which a species persists.
[src:ecology/ecology] Organisms are subject to environmental pressures, but they also modify their habitats.
[src:ecology/ecology] The regulatory feedback between organisms and their environment can affect conditions from local (e.g., a beaver pond) to global scales, over time and even after death, such as decaying logs or silica skeleton deposits from marine organisms.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecosystem engineering is related to niche construction, but the former relates only to the physical modifications of the habitat whereas the latter also considers the evolutionary implications of physical changes to the environment and feedback on natural selection.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecosystem engineers are defined as: "organisms that directly or indirectly modulate the availability of resources to other species, by causing physical state changes in biotic or abiotic materials.
[src:ecology/ecology] Biomes are larger units of organization that categorize regions of the Earth's ecosystems, mainly according to the structure and composition of vegetation.
[src:ecology/ecology] There are different methods to define the continental boundaries of biomes dominated by different functional types of vegetative communities that are limited in distribution by climate, precipitation, weather, and other environmental variables.
[src:ecology/ecology] Biomes include tropical rainforest, temperate broadleaf and mixed forest, temperate deciduous forest, taiga, tundra, hot desert, and polar desert.
[src:ecology/ecology] Other researchers have recently categorized other biomes, such as the human and oceanic microbiomes.
[src:ecology/ecology] To a microbe, the human body is a habitat and a landscape.
[src:ecology/ecology] Microbiomes were discovered largely through advances in molecular genetics, which have revealed a hidden richness of microbial diversity on the planet.
[src:ecology/ecology] The oceanic microbiome plays a significant role in the ecological biogeochemistry of the planet's oceans.
[src:ecology/ecology] The largest scale of ecological organization is the biosphere: the total sum of ecosystems on the planet.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecological relationships regulate the flux of energy, nutrients, and climate all the way up to the planetary scale.
[src:ecology/ecology] For example, the dynamic history of the planetary atmosphere's CO2 and O2 composition has been affected by the biogenic flux of gases coming from respiration and photosynthesis, with levels fluctuating over time in relation to the ecology and evolution of plants and animals.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecological theory has also been used to explain self-emergent regulatory phenomena at the planetary scale: for example, the Gaia hypothesis is an example of holism applied in ecological theory.
[src:ecology/ecology] The Gaia hypothesis states that there is an emergent feedback loop generated by the metabolism of living organisms that maintains the core temperature of the Earth and atmospheric conditions within a narrow self-regulating range of tolerance.
[src:ecology/ecology] Population ecology studies the dynamics of species populations and how these populations interact with the wider environment.
[src:ecology/ecology] A population consists of individuals of the same species that live, interact, and migrate through the same niche and habitat.
[src:ecology/ecology] An example of an introductory population model describes a closed population, such as on an island, where immigration and emigration does not take place.
[src:ecology/ecology] Hypotheses are evaluated with reference to a null hypothesis which states that random processes create the observed data.
[src:ecology/ecology] where *N* is the total number of individuals in the population, *b* and *d* are the per capita rates of birth and death respectively, and *r* is the per capita rate of population change.
[src:ecology/ecology] The formula states that the rate of change in population size ( $\mathrm {d} N(t)/\mathrm {d} t$ ) will grow to approach equilibrium, where ( $\mathrm {d} N(t)/\mathrm {d} t=0$ ), when the rates of increase and crowding are balanced, $r/\alpha$ .
[src:ecology/ecology] Population ecology builds upon these introductory models to further understand demographic processes in real study populations.
[src:ecology/ecology] Commonly used types of data include life history, fecundity, and survivorship, and these are analyzed using mathematical techniques such as matrix algebra.
[src:ecology/ecology] The information is used for managing wildlife stocks and setting harvest quotas.
[src:ecology/ecology] The concept of metapopulations was defined in 1969 as "a population of populations which go extinct locally and recolonize".
[src:ecology/ecology] Metapopulation ecology is another statistical approach that is often used in conservation research.
[src:ecology/ecology] Metapopulation models simplify the landscape into patches of varying levels of quality, and metapopulations are linked by the migratory behaviours of organisms.
[src:ecology/ecology] Animal migration is set apart from other kinds of movement because it involves the seasonal departure and return of individuals from a habitat.
[src:ecology/ecology] Migration is also a population-level phenomenon, as with the migration routes followed by plants as they occupied northern post-glacial environments.
[src:ecology/ecology] Plant ecologists use pollen records that accumulate and stratify in wetlands to reconstruct the timing of plant migration and dispersal relative to historic and contemporary climates.
[src:ecology/ecology] These migration routes involved an expansion of the range as plant populations expanded from one area to another.
[src:ecology/ecology] There is a larger taxonomy of movement, such as commuting, foraging, territorial behavior, stasis, and ranging.
[src:ecology/ecology] Dispersal is usually distinguished from migration because it involves the one-way permanent movement of individuals from their birth population into another population.
[src:ecology/ecology] Community ecology is the study of the interactions among a collection of species that inhabit the same geographic area.
[src:ecology/ecology] Community ecologists study the determinants of patterns and processes for two or more interacting species.
[src:ecology/ecology] Research in community ecology might measure species diversity in grasslands in relation to soil fertility.
[src:ecology/ecology] It might also include the analysis of predator-prey dynamics, competition among similar plant species, or mutualistic interactions between crabs and corals.
[src:ecology/ecology] The underlying concept of an ecosystem can be traced back to 1864 in the published work of George Perkins Marsh ("Man and Nature").
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecosystems may be habitats within biomes that form an integrated whole and a dynamically responsive system having both physical and biological complexes.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecosystem ecology is the science of determining the fluxes of materials (e.g. carbon, phosphorus) between different pools (e.g., tree biomass, soil organic material).
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecosystem ecologists attempt to determine the underlying causes of these fluxes.
[src:ecology/ecology] Research in ecosystem ecology might measure primary production (g C/m^2) in a wetland in relation to decomposition and consumption rates (g C/m^2/y).
[src:ecology/ecology] This requires an understanding of the community connections between plants (i.e., primary producers) and the decomposers (e.g., fungi and bacteria).
[src:ecology/ecology] A food web is the archetypal ecological network.
[src:ecology/ecology] Plants capture solar energy and use it to synthesize simple sugars during photosynthesis.
[src:ecology/ecology] As plants grow, they accumulate nutrients and are eaten by grazing herbivores, and the energy is transferred through a chain of organisms by consumption.
[src:ecology/ecology] The simplified linear feeding pathways that move from a basal trophic species to a top consumer is called the food chain.
[src:ecology/ecology] Food chains in an ecological community create a complex food web.
[src:ecology/ecology] Food webs are a type of concept map used to illustrate and study pathways of energy and material flows.
[src:ecology/ecology] Biodiversity within ecosystems can be organized into trophic pyramids, in which the vertical dimension represents feeding relations that become further removed from the base of the food chain up toward top predators, and the horizontal dimension represents the abundance or biomass at each level.
[src:ecology/ecology] When the relative abundance or biomass of each species is sorted into its respective trophic level, they naturally sort into a 'pyramid of numbers'.
[src:ecology/ecology] Species are broadly categorized as autotrophs (or primary producers), heterotrophs (or consumers), and Detritivores (or decomposers).
[src:ecology/ecology] Autotrophs are organisms that produce their own food (production is greater than respiration) by photosynthesis or chemosynthesis.
[src:ecology/ecology] Heterotrophs are organisms that must feed on others for nourishment and energy (respiration exceeds production).
[src:ecology/ecology] Heterotrophs can be further sub-divided into different functional groups, including primary consumers (strict herbivores), secondary consumers (carnivorous predators that feed exclusively on herbivores), and tertiary consumers (predators that feed on a mix of herbivores and predators).
[src:ecology/ecology] Omnivores do not fit neatly into a functional category because they eat both plant and animal tissues.
[src:ecology/ecology] It has been suggested that omnivores have a greater functional influence as predators because compared to herbivores, they are relatively inefficient at grazing.
[src:ecology/ecology] Trophic levels are part of the holistic or complex systems view of ecosystems.
[src:ecology/ecology] Each trophic level contains unrelated species that are grouped together because they share common ecological functions, giving a macroscopic view of the system.
[src:ecology/ecology] While the notion of trophic levels provides insight into energy flow and top-down control within food webs, it is troubled by the prevalence of omnivory in real ecosystems.
[src:ecology/ecology] A keystone species is a species that is connected to a disproportionately large number of other species in the food-web.
[src:ecology/ecology] Keystone species have lower levels of biomass in the trophic pyramid relative to the importance of their role.
[src:ecology/ecology] The many connections that a keystone species holds means that it maintains the organization and structure of entire communities.
[src:ecology/ecology] The loss of a keystone species results in a range of dramatic cascading effects (termed *trophic cascades*) that alters trophic dynamics, other food web connections, and can cause the extinction of other species.
[src:ecology/ecology] The term keystone species was coined by Robert Paine in 1969 and is a reference to the keystone architectural feature as the removal of a keystone species can result in a community collapse just as the removal of the keystone in an arch can result in the arch's loss of stability.
[src:ecology/ecology] Sea otters (*Enhydra lutris*) are commonly cited as an example because they limit the density of sea urchins that feed on kelp.
[src:ecology/ecology] If sea otters are removed from the system, the urchins graze until the kelp beds disappear, and this has a dramatic effect on community structure.
[src:ecology/ecology] Complexity is understood as a large computational effort needed to assemble numerous interacting parts.
[src:ecology/ecology] Global patterns of biological diversity are complex.
[src:ecology/ecology] This biocomplexity stems from the interplay among ecological processes that influence patterns at different scales, such as transitional areas or ecotones spanning landscapes.
[src:ecology/ecology] Complexity stems from the interplay among levels of biological organization as energy, and matter is integrated into larger units that superimpose onto the smaller parts.
[src:ecology/ecology] Small scale patterns do not necessarily explain larger ones, as in Aristotle's expression "the sum is greater than the parts".
[src:ecology/ecology] Holism is a critical part of the theory of ecology.
[src:ecology/ecology] Holism addresses the biological organization of life that self-organizes into layers of emergent whole systems that function according to non-reducible properties.
[src:ecology/ecology] This means that higher-order patterns of a whole functional system, such as an ecosystem, cannot be predicted or understood by a simple summation of the parts.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecology and evolutionary biology are sister disciplines.
[src:ecology/ecology] Natural selection, life history, development, adaptation, populations, and inheritance thread equally into both.
[src:ecology/ecology] In this framework, the analytical tools of ecologists and evolutionists overlap as they study life through phylogenetics or Linnaean taxonomy.
[src:ecology/ecology] There is no sharp boundary separating ecology from evolution, and they differ more in their areas of applied focus.
[src:ecology/ecology] Both explain properties and processes across different spatial or temporal scales of organization.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecologists study the abiotic and biotic factors that influence evolutionary processes, and evolution can be rapid, occurring on ecological timescales as short as one generation.
[src:ecology/ecology] Even plants express complex behaviour, including memory and communication.
[src:ecology/ecology] Behavioural ecology is the study of an organism's behaviour in its environment and its ecological and evolutionary implications.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ethology is the study of observable movement or behaviour in animals.
[src:ecology/ecology] This could include investigations of motile sperm of plants, mobile phytoplankton, zooplankton swimming toward the female egg, the cultivation of fungi by weevils, the mating dance of a salamander, or social gatherings of amoeba.
[src:ecology/ecology] Adaptation is the central unifying concept in behavioural ecology.
[src:ecology/ecology] Behaviours can be recorded as traits and inherited in much the same way that eye and hair colour can.
[src:ecology/ecology] Behaviours can evolve by means of natural selection as adaptive traits conferring functional utilities that increases reproductive fitness.
[src:ecology/ecology] Cognitive ecology integrates theory and observations from evolutionary ecology and cognitive science, to understand the effect of animal interaction with their habitat on their cognitive systems.
[src:ecology/ecology] "Until recently, however, cognitive scientists have not paid sufficient attention to the fundamental fact that cognitive traits evolved under particular natural settings.
[src:ecology/ecology] Social-ecological behaviours are notable in the social insects, slime moulds, social spiders, human society, and naked mole-rats where eusocialism has evolved.
[src:ecology/ecology] Social behaviours include reciprocally beneficial behaviours among kin and nest mates and evolve from kin and group selection.
[src:ecology/ecology] Kin selection explains altruism through genetic relationships, whereby an altruistic behaviour leading to death is rewarded by the survival of genetic copies distributed among surviving relatives.
[src:ecology/ecology] The social insects, including ants, bees, and wasps are most famously studied for this type of relationship because the male drones are clones that share the same genetic make-up as every other male in the colony.
[src:ecology/ecology] In contrast, group selectionists find examples of altruism among non-genetic relatives and explain this through selection acting on the group; whereby, it becomes selectively advantageous for groups if their members express altruistic behaviours to one another.
[src:ecology/ecology] Groups with predominantly altruistic members survive better than groups with predominantly selfish members.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecological interactions can be classified broadly into a host and an associate relationship.
[src:ecology/ecology] A host is any entity that harbours another that is called the associate.
[src:ecology/ecology] Relationships between species that are mutually or reciprocally beneficial are called mutualisms.
[src:ecology/ecology] Examples of mutualism include fungus-growing ants employing agricultural symbiosis, bacteria living in the guts of insects and other organisms, the fig wasp and yucca moth pollination complex, lichens with fungi and photosynthetic algae, and corals with photosynthetic algae.
[src:ecology/ecology] If there is a physical connection between host and associate, the relationship is called symbiosis.
[src:ecology/ecology] Approximately 60% of all plants, for example, have a symbiotic relationship with arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi living in their roots forming an exchange network of carbohydrates for mineral nutrients.
[src:ecology/ecology] Biogeography is the comparative study of the geographic distribution of organisms and the corresponding evolution of their traits in space and time.
[src:ecology/ecology] The *Journal of Biogeography* was established in 1974.
[src:ecology/ecology] Biogeography and ecology share many of their disciplinary roots.
[src:ecology/ecology] *Island biogeography*, published by Robert MacArthur and Edward O.
[src:ecology/ecology] Wilson in 1967, is one of the fundamentals of ecological theory.
[src:ecology/ecology] Biogeography has a long history in the natural sciences concerning the spatial distribution of plants and animals.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecology and evolution provide the explanatory context for biogeographical studies.
[src:ecology/ecology] Biogeographical patterns result from ecological processes that influence range distributions, such as migration and dispersal. and from historical processes that split populations or species into different areas.
[src:ecology/ecology] The biogeographic processes that result in the natural splitting of species explain much of the modern distribution of the Earth's biota.
[src:ecology/ecology] The splitting of lineages in a species is called vicariance biogeography and it is a sub-discipline of biogeography.
[src:ecology/ecology] There are also practical applications in the field of biogeography concerning ecological systems and processes.
[src:ecology/ecology] For example, the range and distribution of biodiversity and invasive species responding to climate change is a serious concern and active area of research in the context of global warming.
[src:ecology/ecology] r/K selection theory is one of the first predictive models in ecology used to explain life-history evolution.
[src:ecology/ecology] Its premise is that natural selection varies with population density.
[src:ecology/ecology] For example, when an island is first colonized, density of individuals is low.
[src:ecology/ecology] The initial increase in population size is not limited by competition, leaving an abundance of available resources for rapid population growth.
[src:ecology/ecology] These early phases of population growth experience *density-independent* forces of natural selection, which is called *r*-selection.
[src:ecology/ecology] As the population becomes more crowded, it approaches the island's carrying capacity, thus forcing individuals to compete more heavily for fewer available resources.
[src:ecology/ecology] Under crowded conditions, the population experiences density-dependent forces of natural selection, called *K*-selection.
[src:ecology/ecology] In the *r/K*-selection model, the first variable *r* is the intrinsic rate of natural increase in population size and the second variable *K* is the carrying capacity of a population.
[src:ecology/ecology] The relationship between ecology and genetic inheritance predates modern techniques for molecular analysis.
[src:ecology/ecology] Molecular ecological research became more feasible with the development of rapid and accessible genetic technologies, such as the polymerase chain reaction (PCR).
[src:ecology/ecology] The rise of molecular technologies and the influx of research questions into this new field resulted in the publication *Molecular Ecology* in 1992.
[src:ecology/ecology] Molecular ecology uses analytical techniques to study genes in an evolutionary and ecological context.
[src:ecology/ecology] In 1994, John Avise played a leading role in this area of science with the publication of his book, *Molecular Markers, Natural History and Evolution*.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecology is both a biological science and a human science.
[src:ecology/ecology] Human ecology is an interdisciplinary investigation into the ecology of our species.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecology is an employed science of restoration, repairing disturbed sites through human intervention, in natural resource management, and in environmental impact assessments.
[src:ecology/ecology] Wilson predicted in 1992 that the 21st century "will be the era of restoration in ecology".
[src:ecology/ecology] The environment of ecosystems includes both physical parameters and biotic attributes.
[src:ecology/ecology] It is dynamically interlinked and contains resources for organisms at any time throughout their life cycle.
[src:ecology/ecology] Like ecology, the term environment has different conceptual meanings and overlaps with the concept of nature.
[src:ecology/ecology] The biotic environment includes genes, cells, organisms, members of the same species (conspecifics) and other species that share a habitat.
[src:ecology/ecology] A disturbance is any process that changes or removes biomass from a community, such as a fire, flood, drought, or predation.
[src:ecology/ecology] Disturbances are both the cause and product of natural fluctuations within an ecological community.
[src:ecology/ecology] Biodiversity can protect ecosystems from disturbances.
[src:ecology/ecology] The Earth was formed approximately 4.5 billion years ago.
[src:ecology/ecology] As it cooled and a crust and oceans formed, its atmosphere transformed from being dominated by hydrogen to one composed mostly of methane and ammonia.
[src:ecology/ecology] Over the next billion years, the metabolic activity of life transformed the atmosphere into a mixture of carbon dioxide, nitrogen, and water vapor.
[src:ecology/ecology] These gases changed the way that light from the sun hit the Earth's surface and greenhouse effects trapped heat.
[src:ecology/ecology] There were untapped sources of free energy within the mixture of reducing and oxidizing gasses that set the stage for primitive ecosystems to evolve and, in turn, the atmosphere also evolved.
[src:ecology/ecology] Throughout history, the Earth's atmosphere and biogeochemical cycles have been in a dynamic equilibrium with planetary ecosystems.
[src:ecology/ecology] The history is characterized by periods of significant transformation followed by millions of years of stability.
[src:ecology/ecology] The evolution of the earliest organisms, likely anaerobic methanogen microbes, started the process by converting atmospheric hydrogen into methane (4H2 + CO2 → CH4 + 2H2O).
[src:ecology/ecology] Anoxygenic photosynthesis reduced hydrogen concentrations and increased atmospheric methane, by converting hydrogen sulfide into water or other sulfur compounds (for example, 2H2S + CO2 + h*v* → CH2O + H2O + 2S).
[src:ecology/ecology] Early forms of fermentation also increased levels of atmospheric methane.
[src:ecology/ecology] The transition to an oxygen-dominant atmosphere (the *Great Oxidation*) did not begin until approximately 2.4–2.3 billion years ago, but photosynthetic processes started 0.3–1 billion years prior.
[src:ecology/ecology] The biology of life operates within a certain range of temperatures.
[src:ecology/ecology] Heat is a form of energy that regulates temperature.
[src:ecology/ecology] Heat affects growth rates, activity, behaviour, and primary production.
[src:ecology/ecology] Temperature is largely dependent on the incidence of solar radiation.
[src:ecology/ecology] The latitudinal and longitudinal spatial variation of temperature greatly affects climates and consequently the distribution of biodiversity and levels of primary production in different ecosystems or biomes across the planet.
[src:ecology/ecology] Heat and temperature relate importantly to metabolic activity.
[src:ecology/ecology] Poikilotherms have a body temperature largely dependent on the temperature of the external environment.
[src:ecology/ecology] In contrast, homeotherms regulate their internal body temperature by expending metabolic energy.
[src:ecology/ecology] There is a relationship between light, primary production, and ecological energy budgets.
[src:ecology/ecology] Sunlight is the primary input of energy into the planet's ecosystems.
[src:ecology/ecology] Light is composed of electromagnetic energy of different wavelengths.
[src:ecology/ecology] Radiant energy from the sun generates heat, provides photons of light measured as active energy in the chemical reactions of life, and also acts as a catalyst for genetic mutation.
[src:ecology/ecology] Plants, algae, and some bacteria absorb light and assimilate the energy through photosynthesis.
[src:ecology/ecology] Organisms capable of assimilating energy by photosynthesis or through inorganic fixation of H2S are autotrophs.
[src:ecology/ecology] Autotrophs—responsible for primary production—assimilate light energy which becomes metabolically stored as potential energy in the form of biochemical enthalpic bonds.
[src:ecology/ecology] Diffusion of carbon dioxide and oxygen is approximately 10,000 times slower in water than in air.
[src:ecology/ecology] When soils are flooded, they quickly lose oxygen, becoming hypoxic (an environment with O2 concentration below 2 mg/liter) and eventually completely anoxic where anaerobic bacteria thrive among the roots.
[src:ecology/ecology] Water influences the intensity and spectral composition of light as it reflects off the water surface and submerged particles.
[src:ecology/ecology] Salt water plants (halophytes) have additional specialized adaptations, such as the development of special organs for shedding salt and osmoregulating their internal salt (NaCl) concentrations, to live in estuarine, brackish, or oceanic environments.
[src:ecology/ecology] The physiology of fish is adapted to compensate for environmental salt levels through osmoregulation.
[src:ecology/ecology] Their gills form electrochemical gradients that mediate salt excretion in salt water and uptake in fresh water.
[src:ecology/ecology] The shape and energy of the land are significantly affected by gravitational forces.
[src:ecology/ecology] These govern many of the geophysical properties and distributions of biomes across the Earth.
[src:ecology/ecology] On the organismal scale, gravitational forces provide directional cues for plant and fungal growth (gravitropism), orientation cues for animal migrations, and influence the biomechanics and size of animals.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecological traits, such as allocation of biomass in trees during growth are subject to mechanical failure as gravitational forces influence the position and structure of branches and leaves.
[src:ecology/ecology] Climatic and osmotic pressure places physiological constraints on organisms, especially those that fly and respire at high altitudes, or dive to deep ocean depths.
[src:ecology/ecology] These constraints influence vertical limits of ecosystems in the biosphere, as organisms are physiologically sensitive and adapted to atmospheric and osmotic water pressure differences.
[src:ecology/ecology] For example, oxygen levels decrease with decreasing pressure and are a limiting factor for life at higher altitudes.
[src:ecology/ecology] Water transportation by plants is affected by osmotic pressure gradients.
[src:ecology/ecology] Water pressure in the depths of oceans requires that organisms adapt to these conditions.
[src:ecology/ecology] For example, diving animals such as whales, dolphins, and seals are adapted to deal with changes in sound due to water pressure differences.
[src:ecology/ecology] Turbulent forces in air and water affect the environment and ecosystem distribution, form, and dynamics.
[src:ecology/ecology] On a planetary scale, ecosystems are affected by circulation patterns in the global trade winds.
[src:ecology/ecology] Wind power and the turbulent forces it creates can influence heat, nutrient, and biochemical profiles of ecosystems.
[src:ecology/ecology] For example, wind running over the surface of a lake creates turbulence, mixing the water column and influencing the environmental profile to create thermally layered zones, affecting how fish, algae, and other parts of the aquatic ecosystem are structured.
[src:ecology/ecology] Wind speed and turbulence influence evapotranspiration rates and energy budgets in plants and animals.
[src:ecology/ecology] Wind speed, temperature and moisture content vary as winds travel across different land features and elevations.
[src:ecology/ecology] For example, the westerlies come into contact with the coastal and interior mountains of western North America to produce a rain shadow on the leeward side of the mountain.
[src:ecology/ecology] The air expands and moisture condenses as the winds increase in elevation; this is called orographic lift and can cause precipitation.
[src:ecology/ecology] This environmental process produces spatial divisions in biodiversity, as species adapted to wetter conditions are range-restricted to the coastal mountain valleys and unable to migrate across the xeric ecosystems to intermix with sister lineages that are segregated to the interior mountain systems.
[src:ecology/ecology] stages and habitats of varied quality (left).
[src:ecology/ecology] Some species are adapted to forest fires, such as pine trees that open their cones only after fire exposure (right).
[src:ecology/ecology] Plants convert carbon dioxide into biomass and emit oxygen into the atmosphere.
[src:ecology/ecology] By approximately 350 million years ago (the end of the Devonian period), photosynthesis had brought the concentration of atmospheric oxygen above 17%, which allowed combustion to occur.
[src:ecology/ecology] Fire releases CO2 and converts fuel into ash and tar.
[src:ecology/ecology] Fire is a significant ecological parameter that raises many issues pertaining to its control and suppression.
[src:ecology/ecology] While the issue of fire in relation to ecology and plants has been recognized for a long time, Charles Cooper brought attention to the issue of forest fires in relation to the ecology of forest fire suppression and management in the 1960s.
[src:ecology/ecology] Soil is the living top layer of mineral and organic dirt that covers the surface of the planet.
[src:ecology/ecology] It is the chief organizing centre of most ecosystem functions, and it is of critical importance in agricultural science and ecology.
[src:ecology/ecology] The decomposition of dead organic matter (for example, leaves on the forest floor), results in soils containing minerals and nutrients that feed into plant production.
[src:ecology/ecology] The whole of the planet's soil ecosystems is called the pedosphere where a large biomass of the Earth's biodiversity organizes into trophic levels.
[src:ecology/ecology] Invertebrates that feed and shred larger leaves, for example, create smaller bits for smaller organisms in the feeding chain.
[src:ecology/ecology] Collectively, these organisms are the detritivores that regulate soil formation.
[src:ecology/ecology] Soils form composite phenotypes where inorganic matter is enveloped into the physiology of a whole community.
[src:ecology/ecology] As organisms feed and migrate through soils they physically displace materials, an ecological process called bioturbation.
[src:ecology/ecology] This aerates soils and stimulates heterotrophic growth and production.
[src:ecology/ecology] Soil microorganisms are influenced by and are fed back into the trophic dynamics of the ecosystem.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecologists study nutrient budgets to understand how these materials are regulated, flow, and recycled through the environment.
[src:ecology/ecology] This research has led to an understanding that there is global feedback between ecosystems and the physical parameters of this planet, including minerals, soil, pH, ions, water, and atmospheric gases.
[src:ecology/ecology] Six major elements (hydrogen, carbon, nitrogen, oxygen, sulfur, and phosphorus; H, C, N, O, S, and P) form the constitution of all biological macromolecules and feed into the Earth's geochemical processes.
[src:ecology/ecology] From the smallest scale of biology, the combined effect of billions of ecological processes amplify and regulate the biogeochemical cycles of the Earth.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ancient Greek philosophers such as Hippocrates and Aristotle recorded observations on natural history.
[src:ecology/ecology] However, they saw species as unchanging, while varieties were seen as aberrations.
[src:ecology/ecology] Modern ecology sees varieties as the real phenomena, leading to adaptation by natural selection.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecological concepts such as a balance and regulation in nature can be traced to Herodotus (died *c*.
[src:ecology/ecology] 425 BC), who described mutualism in his observation of "natural dentistry".
[src:ecology/ecology] Basking Nile crocodiles, he noted, opened their mouths to give sandpipers safe access to pluck leeches out, giving nutrition to the sandpiper and oral hygiene for the crocodile.
[src:ecology/ecology] Aristotle and his student Theophrastus observed plant and animal migrations, biogeography, physiology, and their behavior, giving an early analogue to the concept of an ecological niche.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecological concepts such as food chains, population regulation, and productivity were developed in the 1700s, through the works of microscopist Antonie van Leeuwenhoek (1632–1723) and botanist Richard Bradley (1688?–1732).
[src:ecology/ecology] Biogeographer Alexander von Humboldt (1769–1859) recognized ecological gradients, where species are replaced or altered in form along environmental gradients.
[src:ecology/ecology] Humboldt drew inspiration from Isaac Newton, as he developed a form of "terrestrial physics".
[src:ecology/ecology] Natural historians, such as Humboldt, James Hutton, and Jean-Baptiste Lamarck laid the foundations of ecology.
[src:ecology/ecology] The term "ecology" (German: *Oekologie, Ökologie*) was coined by Ernst Haeckel in his book *Generelle Morphologie der Organismen* (1866).
[src:ecology/ecology] Haeckel was a zoologist, artist, writer, and later in life a professor of comparative anatomy.
[src:ecology/ecology] Linnaeus founded an early branch of ecology that he called the economy of nature.
[src:ecology/ecology] He influenced Charles Darwin, who adopted Linnaeus' phrase in *The Origin of Species*.
[src:ecology/ecology] Linnaeus was the first to frame the balance of nature as a testable hypothesis.
[src:ecology/ecology] Modern ecology first attracted substantial scientific attention toward the end of the 19th century.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ellen Swallow Richards adopted the term "oekology" in the U.S. as early as 1892.
[src:ecology/ecology] In the early 20th century, ecology transitioned from description to a more analytical form of *scientific natural history*.
[src:ecology/ecology] Frederic Clements published the first American ecology book, *Research Methods in Ecology* in 1905, presenting the idea of plant communities as a superorganism.
[src:ecology/ecology] This launched a debate between ecological holism and individualism that lasted until the 1970s.
[src:ecology/ecology] In 1942, Raymond Lindeman wrote a landmark paper on the trophic dynamics of ecology.
[src:ecology/ecology] Trophic dynamics became the foundation for much work on energy and material flow through ecosystems.
[src:ecology/ecology] Robert MacArthur advanced mathematical theory, predictions, and tests in ecology in the 1950s.
[src:ecology/ecology] Ecology surged in popular and scientific interest during the 1960–1970s environmental movement.
[src:ecology/ecology] In 1962, marine biologist and ecologist Rachel Carson's book *Silent Spring* helped to mobilize the environmental movement by alerting the public to toxic pesticides, such as DDT (C14H9Cl5), bioaccumulating in the environment.
[src:ecology/ecology] Since then, ecologists have worked to bridge their understanding of the degradation of the planet's ecosystems with environmental politics, law, restoration, and natural resources management.
[src:ecology/logy] Philology is an exception: while its meaning is closer to the first sense, the etymology of the word is similar to the second sense.
[src:ecology/logy] In English names for fields of study, the suffix *-logy* is most frequently found preceded by the euphonic connective vowel *o* so that the word ends in *-ology*.
[src:ecology/logy] In these Greek words, the root is always a noun and *-o-* is the combining vowel for all declensions of Greek nouns.
[src:ecology/logy] Linguists sometimes jokingly refer to haplology as *haplogy* (subjecting the word *haplology* to the process of haplology itself).
[src:ecology/logy] Per metonymy, words ending in *-logy* are sometimes used to describe a subject rather than the study of it (e.g., *technology*).
[src:ecology/logy] This usage is particularly widespread in medicine; for example, *pathology* is often used simply to refer to "the disease" itself (e.g., "We haven't found the pathology yet") rather than "the study of a disease".
[src:ecology/logy] Books, journals, and treatises about a subject also often bear the name of this subject (e.g., the scientific journal *Ecology*).
[src:ecology/logy] When appended to other English words, the suffix can also be used humorously to create nonce words (e.g., *beerology* as "the study of beer").
[src:ecology/logy] As with other classical compounds, adding the suffix to an initial word-stem derived from Greek or Latin may be used to lend grandeur or the impression of scientific rigor to humble pursuits, as in *cosmetology* ("the study of beauty treatment") or *cynology* ("the study of dog training").
[src:ecology/logy] The -logy or -ology suffix is commonly used to indicate finite series of art works like books or movies.
[src:ecology/logy] For paintings, the "tych" suffix is more common (e.g. diptych, triptych).
[src:ecology/logy] Further terms like duology (two, mostly in genre fiction) quadrilogy (four) and octalogy (eight) have been coined but are rarely used: for a series of 10, sometimes "decalog" is used (e.g. in the Virgin Decalog) instead of "decalogy".
